---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "How New Managers Can Build Authority Without Being Harsh";
const description = "Authority isn't loud. Learn how new managers can build quiet, steady authority in the first 30 days without being harsh or fake.";
const topic = "Authority";
const number = "04";
const longEmbed = null;
const longWatch = null;
const shorts = [];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "Why First-Time Managers Struggle to Give Feedback and How to Fix It",
    "slug": "/articles/feedback-without-killing-morale/",
    "topic": "Feedback"
  },
  {
    "title": "Why New Managers Say Yes to Everything and Burn Out in 30 Days",
    "slug": "/articles/new-managers-say-yes/",
    "topic": "Capacity"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/build-authority-as-new-manager/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/build-authority-as-new-manager/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>How New Managers Can Build Authority Without Being Harsh</h1>
<p>New managers think authority is a personality.</p>
<p>It is not. Authority is a pattern.</p>
<p>You don&#x27;t need to be louder, older, or tougher than your team. You need to be steady. The team is watching for one thing in your first month: are your signals stable?</p>
<p>If they are, authority builds on its own. If they are not, no title will save you.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>Day one. You want to be liked, and respected. So you swing between two modes.</p>
<p>Mode one: too soft. You ask instead of decide. “Would it be okay if we…?” You let meetings run long. You agree to everything to show you are collaborative.</p>
<p>Mode two: too hard. You feel the softness slipping, so you overcorrect. A sharp email. A sudden hard deadline. A public correction that feels out of proportion.</p>
<p>The team gets whiplash. They don&#x27;t know which version is showing up today. That instability is what kills authority, not your age or your experience.</p>
<p>Authority is not granted on promotion day. It is built, day by day, in small signals.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>If your signals are unstable, the team tests you. Not maliciously. People test unclear boundaries automatically. Deadlines slip. Decisions get re-opened.</p>
<p>You start managing by mood. Good day, you are flexible. Stressed day, you are sharp. The team learns to work around your mood, not with your direction.</p>
<p>You either chase likability or chase control. Both fail. Likability without clarity makes you a peer, not a manager. Control without calm makes you a manager people avoid.</p>
<p>Real authority is quiet. It does not need to be defended every meeting.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is performing authority instead of practicing it.</p>
<p>Performing authority looks like: talking more in meetings, using a serious voice, shutting down pushback fast, making big changes in week one to “set the tone”.</p>
<p>None of that builds real authority. It builds distance.</p>
<p>Authority comes from three boring things, repeated: clarity, consistency, calm.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Build quiet authority with three levers: Decide clearly. Follow through. Stay level.</p>
<p><strong>1. Decide clearly.</strong> One plain decision, out loud. No hedging. “We’re doing A.” You can listen before you decide. Once you decide, state it cleanly. That is 50% of authority.</p>
<p><strong>2. Follow through.</strong> If you said Friday, mean Friday. If you said you’d review it, review it. If you set a standard, hold it next time too. Consistency is what turns a decision into authority. People trust patterns, not speeches.</p>
<p><strong>3. Stay level.</strong> Your voice, your pace, your face. Under pressure, slow down, don’t speed up. Don’t match panic with panic. Don’t match anger with anger. A level signal in a tense room is authority. You don’t need to be cold. Just steady.</p>
<p>That’s it. No harshness required. No fake confidence. Just clear decisions, repeated follow-through, and a level tone.</p>
<p>Authority compounds. Day 5, no one notices. Day 25, the team adjusts to your pace without thinking about it.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Harsh version:</strong> “Guys, I’m the manager now, so we’re doing it my way. I need this by EOD no excuses. Is that clear?”</p>
<p>That buys compliance for one day and resentment for a month.</p>
<p><strong>Quiet authority version:</strong> “Here’s the plan for this week. Ali owns the report, deadline Thursday 2pm. I’ll review once Thursday afternoon. Questions now, then we execute.”</p>
<p>Calm. Named owner. Named deadline. Named checkpoint. No threats. No performance.</p>
<p>The second version gets followed, because it is clear and it will clearly be followed up.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Make three small decisions out loud, cleanly.</strong> No “I think maybe”. Just “We’re doing X”. Practice on low-stakes calls first.</li>
<li><strong>Follow through on two things you already said.</strong> Check your notes from last week. What did you promise? Close those loops today. That is authority building in public.</li>
<li><strong>Slow your pace by 15%.</strong> In your next meeting, speak slightly slower than you want to. Pause before answering questions. Steady pace reads as steady authority.</li>
<li><strong>Hold one standard, kindly.</strong> Pick one missed standard this week – a late update, a messy handoff. Address it calmly with Observation/Impact/Next step. Holding the line once does more than ten speeches.</li>
<li><strong>Stop trying to be liked in meetings.</strong> Aim to be clear instead. Likability follows clarity. It never works the other way around.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>You do not build authority by being harsh. You build it by being predictable.</p>
<p>Clear decision. Consistent follow-through. Level tone. Repeat for 30 days.</p>
<p>The team does not need a strong personality. It needs a stable signal. Be that signal.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
